rComments: This is the worst prof at UTSC. She keeps a sample text for each short answer question and if your answer doesn't match to that text then you will loose marks and probably fail. The TAs also mark unnecessarily hard for no absolute reason.

Very hard exam. I honestly tried so hard in this class by attending lectures, reading textbook and articles and I did not do well at all. You walk out of her exams thinking it was easy and straight forward, but really she is looking for very specific details and marks very hard. Group assignments boost your mark. As a prof, she is a great lecturer.

rComments: Super focused on reading articles LOT's of presentation work Feedback for everything Very clear lectures, always available to explain more
Good prof, exams are a little tough. Make sure to study the articles in detail

She gives good lectures that are clear and simple to follow. Take good notes in class. Her office hours were useful for clarifications. I would urge you to read the articles for the final on your own time as the prof doesn't talk about them and try to really relate the lecture contents to article findings and to real life obesity problems.

rComments: Professor Gadziola is a clear lecturer and she clarifies concepts well. However I found her exams personally to be pretty hard as the question seems general but shes actually looking for specific details. You really need to study very very hard to do well in this course. The group assignments helped boost your mark though.

rComments: Her lectures are clear and she's very approachable. The exams are straightforward, if you re-read the lectures and know the article content you'll be fine. The courseload is pretty heavy (we read 9 research articles), there's a lot of assignments and quizzes but they're easy marks if you stay on top of the material.

I LOVED professor Gadziola. NROC69 was a really hard course but the way she explained concepts and linked them together honestly made the material so much easier to understand. The midterms were fair as they included both multiple choice and short answer questions, one of which was a choice between 2 articles. The final was pretty hard but doable!
